text:
I have DOM content that contains articles using this structure:

```html
<article class="teaser widget brief emphasis-medium bulletin" data-id="1.17007565" data-timestamp="1724040355000" data-author-id="18.24527" data-secondary="" data-perspective="BRIEF" data-ec-list="teaser" data-ec-name="nyhetsmelding">
<div class="bulletin-circle skin-border-600 darkmode-skin-border-400"></div>
<div class="bulletin-wrapper">
<div class="bulletin-compilations compilation-link skin-border">
<!-- include: /serum/render?id=1.13828304&amp;size=18&amp;perspective=REFERENCE&amp;alignment=AUTO --><a href="https://www.nrk.no/nyheter/gassrorledningen-nord-stream-1.13828304" class="compilation widget reference autonomous lp_compilation" data-id="1.13828304" id="innhold">Gassrørledningen Nord Stream</a>
</div>
<div class="bulletin-text text-body">
<time class="relative bulletin-time" datetime="2024-08-19T06:05:55+02:00" data-timestamp="1724040355000">
<a href="https://www.nrk.no/nyheter/1.17007565" class="skin-text-600 darkmode-skin-text-400">
<span class="bulletin-publish-date" style="display: inline;">19. august</span>
<span class="bulletin-publish-year">2024</span>
<span class="bulletin-publish-clock" style="display: inline;">kl.</span>
<span class="bulletin-publish-time">06:05</span>
</a>
</time>
<h2 class="bulletin-title">Russland klagar på tysk Nord Stream-etterforsking</h2>
<div class="bulletin-text-body">
<p>Russland har levert ein formell klage då dei fryktar at den tyske etterforskinga av Nord Stream-sabotasjen blir avslutta utan at dei ansvarlege blir peika ut.</p>
<p>Førre veke etterlyste ein tysk domstol ein ukrainsk dykkarinstruktør i samband med sabotasjen mot gassrøyrleidninga i 2022.</p>
<p>I starten av etterforskinga blei Russland skulda for å stå bak, men seinare har etterforskinga peika i retning Ukraina.</p>
<p>(NTB)</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</article>
```

Please write a Deno script that parses a DOM wrapper node that have a lot of sections like this and create a JSON object with the following structure:

```
{
  "id": "1.17007565",
  "timestamp": 1724040355000,
  "authorId": "18.24527",
  "title": "Russland klagar på tysk Nord Stream-etterforsking",
  "url": "https://www.nrk.no/nyheter/1.17007565",
  "publishDate": "19. august 2024",
  "publishTime": "06:05",
  "body": "...",
}
```



Here's a Deno script that parses the DOM content and creates the JSON structure you want:

```typescript
import { DOMParser } from "https://deno.land/x/deno_dom/deno-dom-wasm.ts";

function parseArticle(articleElement: Element) {
  // Extract basic attributes
  const id = articleElement.getAttribute("data-id");
  const timestamp = parseInt(articleElement.getAttribute("data-timestamp") || "0");
  const authorId = articleElement.getAttribute("data-author-id");

  // Extract title
  const titleElement = articleElement.querySelector(".bulletin-title");
  const title = titleElement?.textContent || "";

  // Extract URL from time link
  const timeLink = articleElement.querySelector("time a");
  const url = timeLink?.getAttribute("href") || "";

  // Extract publish date and time
  const publishDateEl = articleElement.querySelector(".bulletin-publish-date");
  const publishYearEl = articleElement.querySelector(".bulletin-publish-year");
  const publishTimeEl = articleElement.querySelector(".bulletin-publish-time");

  const publishDate = `${publishDateEl?.textContent || ""} ${publishYearEl?.textContent || ""}`.trim();
  const publishTime = publishTimeEl?.textContent || "";

  // Extract body text
  const bodyParagraphs = articleElement.querySelectorAll(".bulletin-text-body p");
  const body = Array.from(bodyParagraphs)
    .map(p => p.textContent)
    .join("\n")
    .trim();

  return {
    id,
    timestamp,
    authorId,
    title,
    url,
    publishDate,
    publishTime,
    body,
  };
}

function parseArticles(htmlContent: string) {
  const parser = new DOMParser();
  const document = parser.parseFromString(htmlContent, "text/html");

  if (!document) {
    throw new Error("Failed to parse HTML content");
  }

  const articles = document.querySelectorAll("article.teaser");
  const results = [];

  for (const article of articles) {
    results.push(parseArticle(article));
  }

  return results;
}

// Usage example:
const htmlContent = `
  <div>
    <!-- Your article HTML here -->
  </div>
`;

try {
  const articles = parseArticles(htmlContent);
  console.log(JSON.stringify(articles, null, 2));
} catch (error) {
  console.error("Error parsing articles:", error);
}
```

This script:

1. Uses `deno_dom` for parsing HTML content
2. Defines a `parseArticle` function that extracts all required fields from a single article element
3. Defines a `parseArticles` function that processes multiple articles from HTML content
4. Returns an array of parsed article objects in the requested format

To use this script:

1. Save it as `parse_articles.ts`
2. Make sure you have Deno installed
3. Run it with:
```bash
deno run --allow-net parse_articles.ts
```

If you want to parse HTML from a file, you can modify the script to read from a file:

```typescript
// Add this at the end instead of the inline HTML content
const htmlContent = await Deno.readTextFile("./articles.html");
```

And run with:
```bash
deno run --allow-read parse_articles.ts
```

The script will handle multiple articles and create an array of JSON objects with the specified structure. Each article will be parsed according to the DOM structure you provided, extracting all the required fields.

Make sure your HTML content is well-formed and matches the structure you provided in the example. If there are variations in the HTML structure, you might need to adjust the selectors and parsing logic accordingly.
